		   <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=698"><span id=>Knolann</span></a><b><span id=></span></b><br>5 posts
		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [4.77]</nobr><br><br><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>Different strokes for different folks :). The reasons Bonds of Force is so highly respected is it gets resisted far less often than root and has a set hold time. Yes, you do need some room to kite the mob, but not that much. If you have to it is possible to even kite something along the zone wall. BoF will not break prematurely on you like root, which has a random hold time (determined when you cast the spell) and a chance to break everytime you nuke. I haven't had much trouble in killing the mob before BoF wears off either, as I can usually empty most of my mana bar in that time as it is. Of course, it is still good to know how long you have until it wears off, so you can prepare to refresh it if needed. Oh, did I mention that I do not have JBoots nor go deliberately seeking SoW (not much anyway :P)? JBoots/SoW is NOT necessary for BoF Kiting, not even the tougher mobs to kite like HGs, which I have kited fine without.<br><br>Root is good, but there are many situations where BoF is better, and vice versa.<br></p><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>-Knolann Caelestis<br> 39th lvl Wizard<br> Tunare</td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >0 Replies</td></tr></table></td></tr></table><tr><td>
